data.content:
**Yes, C# supports `stackalloc`'d `Span<nint>` and `Span<nuint>` — but it requires an `unsafe` context.**

This is because `nint`/`nuint` don't have a compile-time-known size (they're pointer-sized, so 4 or 8 bytes depending on platform). The `stackalloc` expression internally uses `sizeof`, which for native-sized integers is only allowed in `unsafe` blocks (error CS0233).

So the working pattern is:

```csharp
unsafe
{
    Span<nint> span = stackalloc nint[4];
    // works fine
}
```

You'll also need `<AllowUnsafeBlocks>true</AllowUnsafeBlocks>` in your `.csproj`.
